  <div class="box tip">
    <div class="tag"><span class="g">✦</span> On those two numbers</div>
    <p>Yes — you read them correctly, and no, that's not a pricing mistake. The standalone is for the woman who wants to own one course outright with no ongoing anything. Premium is for the woman building the whole business who wants every course as long as she's a member.</p>
    <p>Different questions, different doors. Pick the one that matches yours.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="chapter left reveal">
    <div class="num">The Work</div>
    <div class="orn"><span class="d"></span></div>
    <h2 id="action-plan">Your Pinterest Action Plan</h2>
  </div>

  <p>Seven steps, in order. Do not reorder them — the sequence is the strategy.</p>

  <ol class="list">
    <li><strong>Convert to a business account and claim your website.</strong> Today. Settings → Account management, then Settings → Claimed accounts. Fifteen minutes.</li>
    <li><strong>Download the Pinterest Keyword Planner</strong> and fill it for your first content pillar. Target 30–50 verified keywords. Keywords before everything.</li>
    <li><strong>Build or rename your boards</strong> to match your keyword bank — board title and description both carry the target phrase. Secret the clutter.</li>
    <li><strong>Create your pin templates</strong> in Canva at 1000×1500px. Five or six, not sixty. Make them unmistakably yours at thumbnail size.</li>
    <li><strong>Batch your first two weeks of pins</strong> — multiple fresh pins per article, keyword-layered titles and descriptions.</li>
    <li><strong>Queue them in the native scheduler.</strong> One sitting. Fourteen days. Done.</li>
    <li><strong>Set a monthly analytics date.</strong> One question: what drove outbound clicks? More of that.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>Then repeat steps 5–7 weekly and monthly, forever, at a pace you can actually hold. That's the machine.</p>

