  <div class="chapter reveal">
    <div class="num">Answers</div>
    <div class="orn"><span class="d"></span></div>
    <h2 id="faq">Questions Women Ask Before They Start</h2>
  </div>

  <h3>Do I need a blog to do Pinterest marketing?</h3>
  <p>You need somewhere for the click to land that you control — a blog is the strongest version of that. Pins linking to your own articles build an asset; pins linking nowhere build Pinterest's asset. If your site isn't built yet, start with one cornerstone article and grow from there.</p>

  <h3>How long does Pinterest marketing take to work?</h3>
  <p>Pinterest compounds on a scale of months, not weeks. Plan for a quarter of consistent publishing before you judge results, with growth accelerating as pins accumulate rankings. Anyone promising Pinterest results in a week is describing a different platform.</p>

  <h3>How many times a day should I pin?</h3>
  <p>A few quality, keyword-targeted fresh pins per day is plenty. Consistency over volume — an account that pins modestly every day outperforms an account that pins in unsustainable bursts.</p>

  <h3>Do I have to show my face on Pinterest?</h3>
  <p>No — and Pinterest is the channel where that costs you the least, because searchers come for ideas, not personalities. Your brand's imagery, palette, and point of view do the recognition work a face does elsewhere.</p>

  <h3>Is Pinterest still worth it for business?</h3>
  <p>Pinterest remains one of the highest-intent, longest-shelf-life traffic sources available to a small content business. Its users search with purchase and project intent, and its content keeps distributing long after publication — the opposite of feed-based platforms.</p>

  <h3>What's the difference between fresh pins and repins?</h3>
  <p>A fresh pin is a new image, even if it links to existing content. A repin recirculates an existing image. Pinterest's distribution favors fresh pins — so one article with five pin designs is stronger than five articles with one each.</p>

  <h3>Do I need Tailwind or a paid scheduler?</h3>
  <p>No. Pinterest's native scheduler is free with a business account and queues up to two weeks out, which covers the publishing rhythm this guide teaches. Paid schedulers solve bulk-scheduling and multi-board problems you don't have yet.</p>

